{"title_page": "Circular reporting", "text_new": "\n\n{{Redirect-distinguish|Citogenesis|cytogenesis}}\n{{short description|A problem where a source gets info from somewhere, that then uses that source as a reference}}\n[[File:Circular reporting.svg|thumb|300px|Two basic ways that circular reporting can happen. Dashed lines indicate sourcing that isn't visible to the final reviewer.  In both cases, one original source (top) appears to the final reviewer (bottom) as two independent sources]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n'''Circular reporting''' or '''false confirmation''' is a situation in [[source criticism]] where a piece of information appears to come from multiple independent sources, but in reality comes from only one source.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.army.forces.gc.ca/caj/documents/vol_11/iss_2/CAJ_Vol11.2_12_e.pdf|title=Note to File\u2014The Challenge of Centralized Control Faced by the Intelligence Function in Afghanistan|journal=[[Canadian Army Journal]]|volume=11.2|date=Summer 2008|last1=Sterzer| first1=Marcus| last2=McDuff|first2=Patrick| last3=Flasz|first3=Jacek|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120305201954/http://www.army.forces.gc.ca/caj/documents/vol_11/iss_2/CAJ_Vol11.2_12_e.pdf|archivedate=2012-03-05}}</ref><ref name=\"MotherJones\">{{cite magazine|last=Rozen|first=Laura |url= https://www.motherjones.com/mojoblog/archives/2008/06/8595_three_days_in_r.html|title=The Cocktail Napkin Plan for Regime Change in Iran|date=7 June 2008|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref> In many cases, the problem happens mistakenly through sloppy intelligence-gathering practices. However, at other times the situation can be intentionally contrived by the original source as a way of reinforcing the widespread belief in its information.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hurley |first1=Micheal T. |last2=Smith|first2=Kenton V. |chapter=Chapter 8: The Aviv Report|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EAcUmPdVptIC&pg=PA129|title=I Solemnly Swear: Conmen, Dea, the Media and Pan Am 103|place=New York|publisher=[[iUniverse]]|page=129|isbn=0-595-29947-4|accessdate=2019-06-26|quote=Circular reporting occurs when what is reported is fed back to the originator in revised fashion which makes it difficult to objectively view the end product until you can trace back the sources to determine where the original information actually came from. [[Pan American World Airways|Pan Am]] would eventually try to play that game by trying to introduce into court news reports that they themselves had a hand in producing.}}{{Self-published source|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis problem occurs in a variety of fields, including [[intelligence assessment|intelligence gathering]],<ref name=\"MotherJones\" /> [[echo chamber (media)|journalism]], and scholarly [[research]]. It is of particular concern in [[military intelligence]] because the original source has a higher likelihood of wanting to pass on misinformation, and because the chain of reporting is [[fog of war|more prone to being obscured]]. The case of the 2002 [[Niger uranium forgeries]] was a classic instance of circular reporting by intelligence agencies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/feb/17/nation/na-niger17|title=Niger Uranium Rumors Wouldn't Die|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|quote=This became a classic case of circular reporting,\" said a U.S. intelligence official who spoke on condition of anonymity because he is not authorized to talk to reporters. \"It seemed like we were hearing it from lots of places. People didn't realize it was the same bad information coming in different doors. This is an interesting example of circular reporting.| first1=Bob|last1=Drogin |authorlink1=Bob Drogin| first2=Tom|last2=Hamburger |authorlink2=Tom Hamburger|date=17 February 2006|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Examples involving Wikipedia==\n{{See also|Wikipedia:List of citogenesis incidents|Wikipedia:List of hoaxes on Wikipedia}}\n[[File:Relationship between Wikipedia and the press.svg|thumb|Diagram illustrating circular reporting by Wikipedia and the press]]\n[[Wikipedia]] is sometimes criticized for being used as a source of circular reporting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/media/news/2009/05/wikipedia-hoax-reveals-limits-of-journalists-research.ars |title=Wikipedia hoax points to limits of journalists\u2019 research |website=[[Ars Technica]]|last=Timmer |first=John|date=8 May 2009|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2019/03/wikipedia-citogenesis-circular-reporting-problem.html|title=The Internet\u2019s Dizzying Citogenesis Problem|last=Harrison|first=Stephen|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=7 March 2019|accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> Wikipedia advises researchers and journalists to [[WP:Citing Wikipedia|be wary of, and generally avoid, using Wikipedia as a direct source]], and instead focus on verifiable information found in an article's cited references.<ref>[[Wikipedia:Citing Wikipedia]]</ref>\n\nIn the following examples, false claims were propagated on Wikipedia and in news sources because of circular reporting. [[Randall Munroe]], in his comic ''[[xkcd]]'', called this phenomenon '''citogenesis'''.<ref>{{Cite comic|cartoonist=[[Randall Munroe|Munroe, Randall]]|url= https://xkcd.com/978/|story=Citogenesis|title=[[xkcd]]|issue=978|date=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n*Wikipedia and ''[[The Northern Echo]]'': In January 2014 a statement was anonymously added to the Wikipedia page on UK comedian/broadcaster [[Dave Gorman]] stating that \"he had taken a career break for a sponsored hitch-hike around the Pacific Rim countries\". When this was questioned, an article published at a later date (September 2014) in ''The Northern Echo'', a daily regional newspaper in [[North East England]] was cited as evidence. The falsity of the original claim was confirmed by Gorman in an episode of his UK TV show ''[[Dave Gorman: Modern Life Is Goodish|Modern Life Is Goodish]]'' (first broadcast 22 November 2016).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hardwick|first1=Viv|title=Mears sets his sights on UK|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/entertainment/11460855.Mears_sets_his_sights_on_UK/|accessdate=2019-06-26|work=[[The Northern Echo]]|date=9 September 2014|quote=He once hitchhiked around the Pacific Rim countries|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140929214806/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/entertainment/11460855.Mears_sets_his_sights_on_UK/|archive-date=2014-09-29}}</ref>\n* Wikipedia and ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' in 2009, regarding [[Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bildblog.de/5704/|website=Bildblog|title=Wie ich Freiherr von Guttenberg zu Wilhelm machte|language=de|date=10 February 2009|accessdate=2019-06-26}}<br />{{cite web|url=http://tech.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=09/02/10/2211220|title=False Fact On Wikipedia Proves Itself|author=kdawson|website=[[Slashdot]]|date=11 February 2009|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n* Wikipedia and ''[[The Independent]]'' in 2007, propagating the false information that [[Sacha Baron Cohen]] worked at [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://techdebug.com/blog/2008/04/19/wikipedia-article-creates-circular-references/|title=Wikipedia Article creates Circular references|website=Tech Debug|date=19 April 2009|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n* Wikipedia on the [[coati]] beginning in 2008, when an arbitrary addition \"also known as....the Brazilian aardvark\" by an American student resulted in much subsequent citation and usage of the unsubstantiated nickname as part of the general consensus, including published articles in ''The Independent'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Jonathan|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/from-wallabies-to-chipmunks-the-exotic-creatures-thriving-in-the-uk-2006096.html?action=gallery&ino=5|title=From wallabies to chipmunks, the exotic creatures thriving in the UK|work=The Independent|date=21 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521070548/http://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/from-wallabies-to-chipmunks-the-exotic-creatures-thriving-in-the-uk-2006096.html?action=gallery&ino=5|archive-date=2014-05-21|quote=Coati (also known as the Brazilian aardvark): found in Cumbria}}</ref> the ''[[Daily Express]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Ingham|first=John|url= https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/182018/Exotic-animals-could-wipe-out-native-wildlife|title=Exotic animals could wipe out native wildlife|work=Daily Express|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=2019-07-05|quote=There are also about 10 Brazilian aardvark in Cumbria}}</ref> the ''[[Daily Mail]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2305602/Hunt-runaway-aardvark-Lady-McAlpine-calls-public-help-lost-ring-tailed-coati.html|title=Hunt for the runaway aardvark: Lady McAlpine calls on public to help find her lost ring-tailed coati|last=Williams|first=Amanda|work=Daily Mail|date=8 April 2013|accessdate=2019-07-05|quote=The McAlpine family has appealed for help after a Brazilian aardvark}}</ref> the ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.metro.co.uk/news/831906-scorpions-wallabies-and-aadvarks-invading-britain|title=Scorpions, wallabies and aadvarks 'invading Britain'|work=Metro|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=2019-07-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625121823/https://www.metro.co.uk/news/831906-scorpions-wallabies-and-aadvarks-invading-britain|archive-date=2010-06-25|quote=There are thought to be ten coatis, a kind of Brazilian aardvark, in Cumbria}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Leach|first=Ben|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/wildlife/7841796/Scorpions-Brazilian-aardvarks-and-wallabies-all-found-living-wild-in-UK-study-finds.html|title=Scorpions, Brazilian aardvarks and wallabies all found living wild in UK, study finds|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=2019-07-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625002908/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/wildlife/7841796/Scorpions-Brazilian-aardvarks-and-wallabies-all-found-living-wild-in-UK-study-finds.html|archive-date=2010-06-25}}</ref> a book published by the [[University of Chicago]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Randall|first=Eric |url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/elements/2014/05/how-a-raccoon-became-an-aardvark.html|title=How a Raccoon Became an Aardvark|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=19 May 2014|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref> and a scholarly work published by [[Cambridge University]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Safier|first=Neil|chapter=Beyond Brazilian Nature: The Editorial Itineraries of Marcgraf and Piso\u2019s ''Historia Naturalis Brasiliae''|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pTiNAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA179|title=The Legacy of Dutch Brazil|year=2014|editor-last=Groesen|editor-first=Michiel van|place=New York|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=179|isbn=978-1-107-06117-0|quote=In the case of the Coati, for instance, also known as the Brazilian aardvark, Buffon explained that &ldquo;Marcgrave, and practically all of the Naturalists after him, said that the aardvark had six toes in its hind feet: M. Brisson is the only one who has not copied this error of Marcgrave.&rdquo;}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{external media | width = 210px | float = right | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cSKGa_7XJkg How false news can spread - Noah Tavlin], [[TED (conference)|TED-Ed]]<ref name=\"teded\">{{cite web |title =How false news can spread - Noah Tavlin| publisher =[[TED (conference)|TED-Ed]] |date =27 August 2015|url =http://ed.ted.com/lessons/how-false-news-can-spread-noah-tavlin |accessdate =2019-06-26}}</ref>}}\n\n* [[Circular reasoning]]\n* [[Circular reference]]\n* [[Don't repeat yourself]] (DRY)\n* [[Ghost word]]\n* [[Hoax]]\n* [[Media echo chamber]]\n* [[Reliability of Wikipedia]]\n* [[Rumor]]\n* [[Self-reference]]\n* [[Self-reference effect]]\n* [[Single source of truth]]\n* [[Single version of the truth]]\n* [[System of record]]\n* [[Wikiality]]\n* [[Woozle effect]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Disinformation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Circular reporting}}\n[[Category:Causal fallacies]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Criticism of journalism]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Literary criticism]]\n[[Category:Philosophical logic]]\n", "text_old": "{{stub}}\n{{Redirect-distinguish|Citogenesis|cytogenesis}}\n{{short description|A problem where a source gets info from somewhere, that then uses that source as a reference}}\n[[File:Circular reporting.svg|thumb|300px|Two basic ways that circular reporting can happen. Dashed lines indicate sourcing that isn't visible to the final reviewer.  In both cases, one original source (top) appears to the final reviewer (bottom) as two independent sources]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n'''Circular reporting''' or '''false confirmation''' is a situation in [[source criticism]] where a piece of information appears to come from multiple independent sources, but in reality comes from only one source.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.army.forces.gc.ca/caj/documents/vol_11/iss_2/CAJ_Vol11.2_12_e.pdf|title=Note to File\u2014The Challenge of Centralized Control Faced by the Intelligence Function in Afghanistan|journal=[[Canadian Army Journal]]|volume=11.2|date=Summer 2008|last1=Sterzer| first1=Marcus| last2=McDuff|first2=Patrick| last3=Flasz|first3=Jacek|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120305201954/http://www.army.forces.gc.ca/caj/documents/vol_11/iss_2/CAJ_Vol11.2_12_e.pdf|archivedate=2012-03-05}}</ref><ref name=\"MotherJones\">{{cite magazine|last=Rozen|first=Laura |url= https://www.motherjones.com/mojoblog/archives/2008/06/8595_three_days_in_r.html|title=The Cocktail Napkin Plan for Regime Change in Iran|date=7 June 2008|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref> In many cases, the problem happens mistakenly through sloppy intelligence-gathering practices. However, at other times the situation can be intentionally contrived by the original source as a way of reinforcing the widespread belief in its information.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hurley |first1=Micheal T. |last2=Smith|first2=Kenton V. |chapter=Chapter 8: The Aviv Report|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EAcUmPdVptIC&pg=PA129|title=I Solemnly Swear: Conmen, Dea, the Media and Pan Am 103|place=New York|publisher=[[iUniverse]]|page=129|isbn=0-595-29947-4|accessdate=2019-06-26|quote=Circular reporting occurs when what is reported is fed back to the originator in revised fashion which makes it difficult to objectively view the end product until you can trace back the sources to determine where the original information actually came from. [[Pan American World Airways|Pan Am]] would eventually try to play that game by trying to introduce into court news reports that they themselves had a hand in producing.}}{{Self-published source|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis problem occurs in a variety of fields, including [[intelligence assessment|intelligence gathering]],<ref name=\"MotherJones\" /> [[echo chamber (media)|journalism]], and scholarly [[research]]. It is of particular concern in [[military intelligence]] because the original source has a higher likelihood of wanting to pass on misinformation, and because the chain of reporting is [[fog of war|more prone to being obscured]]. The case of the 2002 [[Niger uranium forgeries]] was a classic instance of circular reporting by intelligence agencies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/feb/17/nation/na-niger17|title=Niger Uranium Rumors Wouldn't Die|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|quote=This became a classic case of circular reporting,\" said a U.S. intelligence official who spoke on condition of anonymity because he is not authorized to talk to reporters. \"It seemed like we were hearing it from lots of places. People didn't realize it was the same bad information coming in different doors. This is an interesting example of circular reporting.| first1=Bob|last1=Drogin |authorlink1=Bob Drogin| first2=Tom|last2=Hamburger |authorlink2=Tom Hamburger|date=17 February 2006|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Examples involving Wikipedia==\n{{See also|Wikipedia:List of citogenesis incidents|Wikipedia:List of hoaxes on Wikipedia}}\n[[File:Relationship between Wikipedia and the press.svg|thumb|Diagram illustrating circular reporting by Wikipedia and the press]]\n[[Wikipedia]] is sometimes criticized for being used as a source of circular reporting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/media/news/2009/05/wikipedia-hoax-reveals-limits-of-journalists-research.ars |title=Wikipedia hoax points to limits of journalists\u2019 research |website=[[Ars Technica]]|last=Timmer |first=John|date=8 May 2009|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2019/03/wikipedia-citogenesis-circular-reporting-problem.html|title=The Internet\u2019s Dizzying Citogenesis Problem|last=Harrison|first=Stephen|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=7 March 2019|accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> Wikipedia advises researchers and journalists to [[WP:Citing Wikipedia|be wary of, and generally avoid, using Wikipedia as a direct source]], and instead focus on verifiable information found in an article's cited references.<ref>[[Wikipedia:Citing Wikipedia]]</ref>\n\nIn the following examples, false claims were propagated on Wikipedia and in news sources because of circular reporting. [[Randall Munroe]], in his comic ''[[xkcd]]'', called this phenomenon '''citogenesis'''.<ref>{{Cite comic|cartoonist=[[Randall Munroe|Munroe, Randall]]|url= https://xkcd.com/978/|story=Citogenesis|title=[[xkcd]]|issue=978|date=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n*Wikipedia and ''[[The Northern Echo]]'': In January 2014 a statement was anonymously added to the Wikipedia page on UK comedian/broadcaster [[Dave Gorman]] stating that \"he had taken a career break for a sponsored hitch-hike around the Pacific Rim countries\". When this was questioned, an article published at a later date (September 2014) in ''The Northern Echo'', a daily regional newspaper in [[North East England]] was cited as evidence. The falsity of the original claim was confirmed by Gorman in an episode of his UK TV show ''[[Dave Gorman: Modern Life Is Goodish|Modern Life Is Goodish]]'' (first broadcast 22 November 2016).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hardwick|first1=Viv|title=Mears sets his sights on UK|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/entertainment/11460855.Mears_sets_his_sights_on_UK/|accessdate=2019-06-26|work=[[The Northern Echo]]|date=9 September 2014|quote=He once hitchhiked around the Pacific Rim countries|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140929214806/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/entertainment/11460855.Mears_sets_his_sights_on_UK/|archive-date=2014-09-29}}</ref>\n* Wikipedia and ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' in 2009, regarding [[Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bildblog.de/5704/|website=Bildblog|title=Wie ich Freiherr von Guttenberg zu Wilhelm machte|language=de|date=10 February 2009|accessdate=2019-06-26}}<br />{{cite web|url=http://tech.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=09/02/10/2211220|title=False Fact On Wikipedia Proves Itself|author=kdawson|website=[[Slashdot]]|date=11 February 2009|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n* Wikipedia and ''[[The Independent]]'' in 2007, propagating the false information that [[Sacha Baron Cohen]] worked at [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://techdebug.com/blog/2008/04/19/wikipedia-article-creates-circular-references/|title=Wikipedia Article creates Circular references|website=Tech Debug|date=19 April 2009|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n* Wikipedia on the [[coati]] beginning in 2008, when an arbitrary addition \"also known as....the Brazilian aardvark\" by an American student resulted in much subsequent citation and usage of the unsubstantiated nickname as part of the general consensus, including published articles in ''The Independent'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Jonathan|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/from-wallabies-to-chipmunks-the-exotic-creatures-thriving-in-the-uk-2006096.html?action=gallery&ino=5|title=From wallabies to chipmunks, the exotic creatures thriving in the UK|work=The Independent|date=21 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521070548/http://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/from-wallabies-to-chipmunks-the-exotic-creatures-thriving-in-the-uk-2006096.html?action=gallery&ino=5|archive-date=2014-05-21|quote=Coati (also known as the Brazilian aardvark): found in Cumbria}}</ref> the ''[[Daily Express]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Ingham|first=John|url= https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/182018/Exotic-animals-could-wipe-out-native-wildlife|title=Exotic animals could wipe out native wildlife|work=Daily Express|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=2019-07-05|quote=There are also about 10 Brazilian aardvark in Cumbria}}</ref> the ''[[Daily Mail]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2305602/Hunt-runaway-aardvark-Lady-McAlpine-calls-public-help-lost-ring-tailed-coati.html|title=Hunt for the runaway aardvark: Lady McAlpine calls on public to help find her lost ring-tailed coati|last=Williams|first=Amanda|work=Daily Mail|date=8 April 2013|accessdate=2019-07-05|quote=The McAlpine family has appealed for help after a Brazilian aardvark}}</ref> the ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.metro.co.uk/news/831906-scorpions-wallabies-and-aadvarks-invading-britain|title=Scorpions, wallabies and aadvarks 'invading Britain'|work=Metro|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=2019-07-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625121823/https://www.metro.co.uk/news/831906-scorpions-wallabies-and-aadvarks-invading-britain|archive-date=2010-06-25|quote=There are thought to be ten coatis, a kind of Brazilian aardvark, in Cumbria}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Leach|first=Ben|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/wildlife/7841796/Scorpions-Brazilian-aardvarks-and-wallabies-all-found-living-wild-in-UK-study-finds.html|title=Scorpions, Brazilian aardvarks and wallabies all found living wild in UK, study finds|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=2019-07-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625002908/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/wildlife/7841796/Scorpions-Brazilian-aardvarks-and-wallabies-all-found-living-wild-in-UK-study-finds.html|archive-date=2010-06-25}}</ref> a book published by the [[University of Chicago]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Randall|first=Eric |url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/elements/2014/05/how-a-raccoon-became-an-aardvark.html|title=How a Raccoon Became an Aardvark|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=19 May 2014|accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref> and a scholarly work published by [[Cambridge University]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Safier|first=Neil|chapter=Beyond Brazilian Nature: The Editorial Itineraries of Marcgraf and Piso\u2019s ''Historia Naturalis Brasiliae''|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pTiNAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA179|title=The Legacy of Dutch Brazil|year=2014|editor-last=Groesen|editor-first=Michiel van|place=New York|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=179|isbn=978-1-107-06117-0|quote=In the case of the Coati, for instance, also known as the Brazilian aardvark, Buffon explained that &ldquo;Marcgrave, and practically all of the Naturalists after him, said that the aardvark had six toes in its hind feet: M. Brisson is the only one who has not copied this error of Marcgrave.&rdquo;}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{external media | width = 210px | float = right | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cSKGa_7XJkg How false news can spread - Noah Tavlin], [[TED (conference)|TED-Ed]]<ref name=\"teded\">{{cite web |title =How false news can spread - Noah Tavlin| publisher =[[TED (conference)|TED-Ed]] |date =27 August 2015|url =http://ed.ted.com/lessons/how-false-news-can-spread-noah-tavlin |accessdate =2019-06-26}}</ref>}}\n\n* [[Circular reasoning]]\n* [[Circular reference]]\n* [[Don't repeat yourself]] (DRY)\n* [[Ghost word]]\n* [[Hoax]]\n* [[Media echo chamber]]\n* [[Reliability of Wikipedia]]\n* [[Rumor]]\n* [[Self-reference]]\n* [[Self-reference effect]]\n* [[Single source of truth]]\n* [[Single version of the truth]]\n* [[System of record]]\n* [[Wikiality]]\n* [[Woozle effect]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Disinformation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Circular reporting}}\n[[Category:Causal fallacies]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Criticism of journalism]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Literary criticism]]\n[[Category:Philosophical logic]]\n", "name_user": "Rpyle731", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_reporting"}
{"title_page": "List of Puerto Rican writers", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{|class=\"infobox bordered\" style=\"width: 22em; font-size: 95%; text-align: left;\" cellpadding=\"3\"\n! colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:larger; background:silver; color:Black;\"|Puerto Rican writers<br/>[[File:Flag of Puerto Rico.svg|25px|center]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |<div style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">\n[[File:ATapia2.jpg|x92px|Tapia Rivera]][[File:Alejandrina Benitez de Gautier.jpg|x92px|Benitez de Gautier]][[File:Jos\u00e9 Gautier Ben\u00edtez (small).jpg|x90px|Benitez]]<br/>[[File:Retrato de EMdeHostos por Francisco Oller.jpg|x103px|de Hostos]][[File:Antonio S. Pedreira.JPG|x106px|Pedreira]][[File:Lola Rodriguez de Tio.jpg|x106px|Rodr\u00edguez de Ti\u00f3]]<br/><small>First row:<br/>[[Alejandro Tapia y Rivera]]{{\u2022}}[[Alejandrina Benitez de Gautier]]<br/>[[Jos\u00e9 Gautier Ben\u00edtez]]<br/>Second row:<br/>[[Eugenio Mar\u00eda de Hostos]]{{\u2022}}[[Antonio S. Pedreira]]<br/>[[Lola Rodr\u00edguez de Ti\u00f3]]</small>\n|}\nThis is a list of [[Puerto Rican literature|Puerto Rican literary]] figures, including [[poet]]s, [[novelist]]s, [[short story|short story authors]], and [[playwright]]s. It includes people who were born in Puerto Rico, people who are of Puerto Rican ancestry, and many long-term residents and/or immigrants who have made Puerto Rico their home, and who are recognized for their literary work. New entries must be placed in alphabetical order and follow the formatting for the list.\n\n<!-- Read carefully before adding a name to this list! -->\n<!-- This list should contain the names of persons who meet the pre-established Notability criteria, even if the person does not have an article yet. Additions to the list must be listed in the appropriate alphabet section and in alphabetical order by surname. -->\n<!-- Each addition to the list must also provide a reliable verifiable source which cites the person's notability and the person's link to Puerto Rico, otherwise the name will be removed. -->\n\n==A==\n{{div col}}\n* '''[[Manuel Abreu Adorno]]''' (1955\u20131984), novelist<ref name=Torres/>\n* '''Rafael Acevedo''' (born 1960), poet, playwright, fiction writer<ref name=Torres/>\n* '''[[Alfredo M. Aguayo]]''', educator and writer (1866\u20131948) <br />''Established the first laboratory of child psychology at the University of Havana''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salonhogar.com/est_soc/pr/pueblos/ponce/index.htm |title=Ponce |publisher=Salonhogar.com |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Jack Ag\u00fceros]]''' (1934\u20132014), author, playwright, poet and translator<ref>[http://www.martinespada.net/Jack%20Agueros.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090812021128/http://www.martinespada.net/Jack%20Agueros.htm |date=12 August 2009 }}</ref>\n* '''[[Miguel Algar\u00edn]]''' (born 1941), poet, writer<br />''Co-founder of the [[Nuyorican Poets Cafe]].''<ref name=\"MA\">{{cite web|url=http://miguelalgarin.com/ |title=miguelalgarin.com |publisher=miguelalgarin.com |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Manuel A. Alonso]]''' (1822\u20131889), poet and author<br />''Considered by many to be the first Puerto Rican writer of notable importance.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuertorico.org/culture/famousprA-C.shtml |title=Puerto Rico's Culture: Famous Puerto Ricans: A-C |publisher=Topuertorico.org |accessdate=12 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329114815/http://www.topuertorico.org/culture/famousprA-C.shtml |archivedate=29 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Silvia \u00c1lvarez Curbelo]]''' (born 1940), writer and historian<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edicionescallejon.com/autor.php5?aid=14 |title=Ediciones Callej\u00f3n |publisher=Edicionescallejon.com |accessdate=12 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707055912/http://www.edicionescallejon.com/autor.php5?aid=14 |archivedate=7 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Alba Ambert]]''', novelist<br>''Ambert in 1996, became the first Hispanic author to win the Carey McWilliams Award for Multicultural Literature, presented by the Multicultural Review, for her novel'' A Perfect Silence.<ref name=\"HF\">\"Hispanic Firsts\", By; Nicolas Kanellos, publisher Visible Ink Press; {{ISBN|0-7876-0519-0}}; p.40</ref>\n* '''[[Marta Aponte Alsina]]''' (born 1945), storyteller, novelist and literary critic<ref name=Torres/>\n* '''[[Pedro Aponte V\u00e1zquez|Pedro I. Aponte V\u00e1zquez]]''', historian, journalist, social scientist, professor and writer<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5b2dnzu54ZEC&pg=PT431 |title=American Gunfight: The Plot to Kill Harry Truman--and the Shoot-out that Stopped it |first1= Stephen |last1= Hunter |first2=John |last2=Bainbridge |location=New York |publisher=Simon & Schuster |year=2005 |accessdate=22 October 2013|isbn=9780743281959 }} |page=Source Notes #27. Page 431. (Evidences notability)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albany.edu/~scifraud/data/sci_fraud_4803.html |last=Starr |first=Douglas |title=Revisiting a 1930s Scandal, AACR to Rename a Prize,\" Science 300 (25 April 2003) |pages=573\u2013574 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511051109/http://www.albany.edu/~scifraud/data/sci_fraud_4803.html |archivedate=11 May 2013 }} A. C. Higgins. Science Fraud Database. SUNY at Albany. 2013. (Evidences Puerto Rican background.)</ref><br>Author of ''\u00a1Yo Acuso! Tortura y Asesinato de Don Pedro Albizu Campos.'';<ref>(Bayamon, PR: Movimiento Ecumenico Nacional de Puerto Rico. 1985). Reprinted (Paperback. 1991)</ref> ''Pedro Albizu Campos: Su persecuci\u00f3n por el F.B.I.'';<ref>(Publicaciones Ren\u00e9, 1991. 77 pages)</ref> ''Cr\u00f3nica de un encubrimiento: Albizu Campos y el caso Rhoads.'';<ref>(San Juan: Publicaciones REN\u00c9, 1992) [co-authored with Gregorio Hernandez Rivera]</ref> ''Locura por decreto: El papel de Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn y Jos\u00e9 Tr\u00edas Monge en el diagn\u00f3stico de locura de don Pedro Albizu Campos.'';<ref>(San Juan: Publicaciones REN\u00c9, 1994)</ref> ''El ataque Nacionalista a La Fortaleza'';<ref>Gregorio Hern\u00e1ndez Rivera. Pedro I. Aponte V\u00e1zquez, editor. (Publisher: Publicaciones REN\u00c9. 1993. 978-1-931702-01-0)</ref> ''The Unsolved Case of Dr. Cornelius P. Rhoads: An Indictment.'';<ref>(Publisher, Publicaciones Ren\u00e9. 2005. ISBN, 1931702071)</ref> ''Transici\u00f3n'' [short stories];<ref>(Publisher: Los Libros de la Iguana. 2010. 113 pages)</ref> ''La hacienda'';<ref>(Publisher: Publicaciones Ren\u00e9. 2011. 42 pages)</ref> ''\"Necator Americanus: O sobre la fisiolog\u00eda del caso Rhoads\"''<ref>(Revista del Colegio de Abogados de Puerto Rico, Vol. 43, N\u00fam. 1, Febrero, 1982, pp. 117-142.)</ref>\n* '''[[Delma S. Arrigoitia]]''', historian, author<br />''Arrigoitia was the first person in the University of Puerto Rico to earn a master's degree in the field of history. In 2010, her book, \"Puerto Rico Por Encima de Todo: Vida y Obra de Antonio R. Barcelo, 1868\u20131938\", was recognized among the best in the category of \"research and criticism\" and awarded a first place prize by the [[Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prdailysun.com/news/Best-books-recognized-by-Ateneo |accessdate=14 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009105014/http://www.prdailysun.com/news/Best-books-recognized-by-Ateneo |archivedate=9 October 2011 }}</ref>\n* '''[[Francisco Arriv\u00ed]]''', writer, poet, and playwright<br /> ''Arriv\u00ed is known as \"The Father of the Puerto Rican Theater\".''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biblioteca.uprh.edu/cultural/biografias/letra%20a/Francisco%20Arrivi.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-04-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303214407/http://biblioteca.uprh.edu/cultural/biografias/letra%20a/Francisco%20Arrivi.htm |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Rane Arroyo]]''', poet, playwright and scholar<ref>{{cite web|author=Robin Becker |url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/rane-arroyo |title=Rane Arroyo |publisher=The Poetry Foundation |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref> \n* '''[[Yolanda Arroyo Pizarro]]''' (born 1970), an award-winning Puerto Rican novelist, short story writer and essayist.\n{{div col end}}\n\n==B-C==\n{{div col}}\n* '''[[Lefty (Manuel) Barreto]]''', novelist, author of autobiography ''Nobody's Hero'' (1977)<ref name=Zimmerman>listed in Marc Zimmerman, ''U.S. Latino Literature: An Essay and Annotated Bibliography'', MARCH/Abrazo, 1992.</ref>\n* '''[[Janette Becerra]]''', short-story writer, poet, professor, literary critic, and lawyer. Author of ''Doce versiones de soledad'', ''Elusiones'', and ''Antr\u00f3polis''.\n* '''[[Emilio S. Belaval]]''', short-story writer, playwright, essayist, and lawyer<ref name=\"PRE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.enciclopediapr.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=09121704 |title=Language and Literature: Belaval Maldonado Emilio S |publisher=Enciclopediapr.org |accessdate=12 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313001112/http://www.enciclopediapr.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=09121704 |archivedate=13 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Pura Belpr\u00e9]]''', author<br />''First Puerto Rican librarian in New York City.''<ref>\"Pura Belpr\u00e9: The Children's Ambassador\". In Vicki Ruiz and Virginia S\u00e1nchez Korrol, ''Latina Legacies: Identity, Biography, and Community'' New York: Oxford University Press, 2005. 148-157</ref>\n* '''[[Samuel Beniquez]]''', author<br />''Author of the autobiographical book entitled: Tu alto precio... Mi gran valor.''<ref>{{cite web |title=First page of the newspaper \"Primera Hora\" of Puerto Rico and subsequent pages 2 through 4. Edition of January 20, 2012 |url=http://www.primerahora.com/pruebadeadnparalidermita-604429.html |publisher=Primerahora.com}}</ref>\n* '''[[Mar\u00eda Bibiana Ben\u00edtez]]''', playwright<br /> ''Benitez is one of Puerto Rico's \"first\" poetesses''.<ref name=\"MVC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.enciclopediapr.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=08112102 |title=Language and Literature: Ben\u00edtez, Mar\u00eda Bibiana |publisher=Enciclopediapr.org |date=17 January 2010 |accessdate=12 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233048/http://www.enciclopediapr.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=08112102 |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Alejandrina Ben\u00edtez de Gautier]]''', poet<br />''Ben\u00edtez de Gautier's collaboration with the \"Aguinaldo Puertorrique\u00f1o\" (Collection of Puerto Rican Poetry) gave her recognition as a great poet.''<ref name=\"AL\">http://artesliberales.bc.inter.edu/jquintana/TodoWeb/Todo%20PR/Biograf%EDas/Bb.htm{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* '''[[Tom\u00e1s Blanco (writer)|Tom\u00e1s Blanco]]''', writer and historian<br /> ''Blanco was the author of \"Prontuario Historico de Puerto Rico\" and \"El Prejuicio Racial en Puerto Rico\" (Racial Prejudice in Puerto Rico).''<ref name=\"ENDI\"/>\n* '''[[Juan Boria]]''', Afro-Caribbean poet<br />''Boria, also known as the '''Negro Verse Pharaoh''', was a poet known for his Afro-Caribbean poetry.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prpop.org/biografias/j_bios/JuanBoria.shtml |title=Juan Boria |publisher=Prpop.org |accessdate=12 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120913185902/http://www.prpop.org/biografias/j_bios/JuanBoria.shtml |archivedate=13 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*'''[[Gerson Borrero]]''', journalist, radio host and TV commentator in New York City. He has been editor-at-large of City & State NY and editor-in-chief of [[El Diario/La Prensa]]<ref>[https://www.cityandstateny.com/articles/opinion/podcast-gerson-borrero-reveals-cuomos-new-secretary-of-state.html ''City & State''; Feb. 3, 2016; \u201cGerson Borrero reveals Cuomo\u2019s new Secretary of State\u2019\u2019]</ref>\n* '''[[Giannina Braschi]]''', Vanguard poet, Spanglish novelist, and performer of spoken word. Titles: \"[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]\", \"Empire of Dreams\", and \"[[United States of Banana]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/bookfest/author/giannina_braschi |title=Giannina Braschi &#124; National Book Festival - Library of Congress |publisher=Loc.gov |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref><ref>''The Review of Contemporary Fiction'', Review of Giannina Braschi's ''Yo-Yo Boing'', by David William Foster, 1999.</ref>\n* '''[[Julia de Burgos]]''', one of the greatest poets to have been born in Puerto Rico; author of \"Yo misma fui mi ruta\" and \"Poema R\u00edo Grande de Lo\u00edza\".''<ref>{{cite web|author=John K |url=http://jstheater.blogspot.com/2005/04/poem-julia-de-burgoss-to-julia-de.html |title=J'S THEATER: Poem: Julia de Burgos's \"To Julia de Burgos\" |publisher=Jstheater.blogspot.com |date=8 April 2005 |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Pedro Cabiya]]''', writer, poet and filmmaker. Author of the seminal ''Historias tremendas''. Other books include ''Historias atroces, La cabeza, Malas hierbas, Trance, Crazy X-Ray Boomeranf Girl, \u00c1nima Sola, Phantograms'' and ''Saga de Sandulce.'' <ref>Morales Boscio, Cynthia. La incertidumbre del ser. San Juan, Puerto Rico. Isla Negra Editores, 2009.</ref>\n* '''[[List of Puerto Rican women writers|Mayra Calvani]]''', writer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.authorsden.com/mayracalvani |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927233958/http://www.authorsden.com/mayracalvani |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 September 2007 |title=Mayra Calvani (author) on AuthorsDen |publisher=Authorsden.com |date=26 June 2007 |accessdate=12 March 2014 }}</ref> \n* '''[[Zenobia Camprub\u00ed]]''', writer/poet (Puerto Rican mother)<br />''Camprub\u00ed was also the wife of Nobel Prize winning author [[Juan Ram\u00f3n Jim\u00e9nez]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccgediciones.com/Sala_de_Estar/Biografias/ZenobiaCA.htm |title=Zenobia Camprub\u00ed Aymar |language=es |publisher=Ccgediciones.com |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Nemesio Canales]]''', essayist and poet<ref name=\"ENDI\"/>\n* '''[[Luisa Capetillo]]''', labor activist<br />'' Capetillo was one of Puerto Rico's most famous labor organizers. She was also a writer and an anarchist who fought for workers and women's rights.''<ref>[http://www.lucyparsonsproject.org/anarchism/aldebol_luisa_capetillo.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218082834/http://www.lucyparsonsproject.org/anarchism/aldebol_luisa_capetillo.html |date=18 February 2012 }}</ref>\n* '''[[Jaime Carrero]]''', poet and playwright<ref name=Torres/><ref name=Zimmerman/>\n* '''[[N. Humberto Cintr\u00f3n]]''', novelist, author of ''Frankie Christo'' (1972)<ref name=Zimmerman/>\n* '''[[Joaqu\u00edn Col\u00f3n]]''' (1896\u20131964), author of ''Pioneros puertorrique\u00f1os en Nueva York''<ref>[http://www.latinoteca.com/app-home/app-information/Publications/authorIndex/showBookDetails?code=9781558853355 ]{{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Manuel Corchado y Juarbe]]''', poet, journalist and politician<br />''Corchado y Juarbe defended the abolition of slavery and the establishment of a University in Puerto Rico.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://isabelapr.org/manuel_corchado.htm |title=Manuel Corchado |publisher=Isabelapr.org |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Juan Antonio Corretjer]]''', poet<br />''Corretjer was also a journalist and pro-independence political activist who opposed United States rule in Puerto Rico.''.<ref name=\"PRCC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prcc-chgo.org/ |title=prcc-chgo.org |publisher=prcc-chgo.org |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Zo\u00e9 Corretjer Llor\u00e9ns]]'''<ref>El surrealismo en la novela hispanoamericana. Luis Rafael S\u00e1nchez y \"La guaracha del Macho Camacho\". 2007.</ref><ref>\"La\u00edberinto en dos tiempos\". 2010.</ref>\n* '''[[Nicky Cruz]]''', reverend<br />''Cruz has written two autobiographies, ''Run Baby Run'', with Jamie Buckingham (1968), and ''Soul Obsession'', with Frank Martin (2005).''<ref name=rbr>\"Run, Baby, Run\"; Nicky Cruz (Author); Publisher: Bridge-Logos (1 December 1988); {{ISBN|978-0-88270-630-6}}</ref>\n* '''[[Victor Hern\u00e1ndez Cruz]]''', poet and essayist. Random House published Cruz's first poetry collection, ''Snaps'' (1969), when he was nineteen.\n* '''[[Isabel Cuch\u00ed Coll]]''', journalist and author<br>''Cuchi Coll was the granddaughter of [[Cayetano Coll y Toste]] and niece of [[Jos\u00e9 Coll y Cuch\u00ed]]. She served as Director of the \"Sociedad de Autores Puertorrique\u00f1o''<ref>\"Tras las Huellas de Nuestro Paso\"; by: Ildelfonso L\u00f3pez; Publisher: AEELA, 1998</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==D==\n{{div col}}\n* '''[[\u00c1njelamar\u00eda D\u00e1vila]]''', poet<ref name=Torres/>\n* '''[[Jos\u00e9 Antonio D\u00e1vila]]''', poet<br />''D\u00e1vila was a well-known poet during Puerto Rico's postmodern era of poetry.''\n* '''[[Virgilio D\u00e1vila]]''', poet<br />'' D\u00e1vila is considered by many to be one of Puerto Rico's greatest representatives of the modern literary era.''<ref name=\"ND\"/>\n* '''[[Anjanette Delgado]]''', novelist, author of \"The Heartbreak Pill\" and \"The Clairvoyant of Calle Ocho.\" Twice winner of the International Latino Book Award.<ref>{{cite news|author=Amy Reyes|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/entertainment/books/article2651463.html |title=Interview: Anjanette Delgado and 'The Clairvoyant of Calle Ocho'|location=Miami |newspaper=The Miami Herald|date= October 12, 2014|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref> \n* '''[[Nelson Antonio Denis]]''', novelist, journalist, New York State Assemblyman<br>''Denis authored '''War Against All Puerto Ricans''', published over 300 editorials as the Editorial Director of [[El Diario/La Prensa]], and received the \"Best Editorial Writing\" award from the'' [[National Association of Hispanic Journalists]].<ref>[http://www.manhattantimesnews.com/2011/qjuan-boboq-chapter-1.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007091116/http://www.manhattantimesnews.com/2011/qjuan-boboq-chapter-1.html |date=7 October 2011 }}</ref> \n* '''[[Abelardo D\u00edaz Alfaro]]''', writer<ref>{{cite news|author=William H. Honan |author-link=William H. Honan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/26/books/abelardo-diaz-alfaro-81-author-of-puerto-rican-stories.html |title=Abelardo Diaz Alfaro, 81; Author of Puerto Rican Stories - New York Times |location=Puerto Rico |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= 26 July 1999|accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Emilio D\u00edaz Valc\u00e1rcel]]'''<ref name=Torres/>\n* '''[[Jaquira D\u00edaz]]''', writer, journalist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://therumpus.net/2016/08/visible-women-writers-of-color-4-jaquira-diaz/|title=VISIBLE: Women Writers of Color: Jaquira D\u00edaz|website=TheRumpus.com|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> \n* '''[[Jos\u00e9 de Diego]]''', \"The Father of the Puerto Rican Independence Movement\"<br>''De Diego was then elected to the House of Delegates, the only locally elected body of government allowed by the U.S., and which De Diego presided from 1904 to 1917''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/#sclient=psy&hl=en&safe=off&rlz=1R2SKPB_enAE382&tbs=bks:1&q=Jos%C3%A9%20de%20Diego%20Felipe%20Diego%20Elisa%20Mart%C3%ADnez&rlz=1R2SKPB_enAE382&aq=f&aqi=&aql=&oq=&gs_rfai=&pbx=1&fp=f46a8ee5cacb00ff|title=Google}}</ref> \n* '''[[Caridad de la Luz]]''' a.k.a. ''La Bruja'' is a poet, playwright, actress and activist.<br />She is also the writer/actor of ''Boogie Rican Blvd.''<ref name=\"LP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eldiariony.com/noticias/especiales/detail.aspx?EspecialId=26&id=1098418|title=P\u00e1gina no encontrada - El Diario NY|access-date=17 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.or